   "source": [
    "# Taylor models of univariate functions\n",
    "\n",
    "(by Sean Cowan)\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook introduces the application of Taylor models to univariate functions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "048fec6e-9c23-40b1-ae72-1b7354a3f4d3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Importing stuff"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "bc1c4a85-2c69-4099-ab75-a66cbdd520ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from pyaudi import gdual_double as gdual, taylor_model, int_d\n",
    "from pyaudi import exp, log, sin\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy as sci\n",
    "from itertools import product\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import matplotlib.colors as col\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "\n",
    "from plotting_functions import plot_orders"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4ca1a371-823f-4fe5-af2a-42f1de23d503",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Exponential\n",
    "\n",
    "First, an exponential function is used to plot the Taylor Model of the function on the domain $[-0.5, 0.5]$. The exponential is chosen as it monotically increases, which should make it easy for a truncated Taylor series of a low order to approximate the function reasonably well. The function is defined as:\n",
    "$$f(x) = e^x$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "16136b28-e5f4-4488-80a9-ae40b93594fa",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def func(x):\n",
    "    if isinstance(x, taylor_model):\n",
    "        return exp(x)\n",
    "    elif isinstance(x, float):\n",
    "        return np.exp(1) ** x\n",
    "\n",
    "domain_size = 0.5\n",
    "exp_points = {\"x\": 0.0}\n",
    "dom = {\"x\": int_d(exp_points[\"x\"] - domain_size, exp_points[\"x\"] + domain_size)}\n",
    "rem = int_d(0.0, 0.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax = plot_orders(func, rem, exp_points, dom, orders=[2, 3, 4], buffer=0.0)\n",
    "ax.grid()\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('x')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('f(x)'); # <-- to suppress notebook text output\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "6ce9599c-02aa-43fa-bae4-07195e19b422",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = plot_orders(func, rem, exp_points, dom, orders=[2, 3, 4], buffer=0.0)\n",
    "ax.grid()\n",
    "ax.set_xlim([0.35, 0.3525])\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([1.395, 1.45])\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('x')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('f(x)');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2fe82ed6-490c-400f-b0a8-b861052650e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Sine wave\n",
    "\n",
    "Second, the Taylor model of a sine function is plotted on the domain $[0, 2 \\pi]$. The sine wave is periodic, and therefore more difficult to approximate. It can be seen that higher orders are needed to approximate the function with the same level of accuracy as compared to the exponential function. The function is defined as:\n",
    "$$f(x) = \\sin(x)$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "179bf7d1-b9c4-494b-9373-a847b3adb58e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def func(x):\n",
    "    if isinstance(x, taylor_model):\n",
    "        return sin(x)\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return np.sin(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "domain_size = 3.14\n",
    "exp_points = {\"x\": 0.0}\n",
    "dom = {\"x\": int_d(exp_points[\"x\"] - domain_size, exp_points[\"x\"] + domain_size)}\n",
    "rem = int_d(0.0, 0.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax = plot_orders(func, rem, exp_points, dom, orders=[4, 5, 6], buffer=0.0)\n",
    "ax.grid()\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([-5, 5])\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('f(x)')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('x');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "81aa9fc9-cf65-4238-9ec0-516579c92b68",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here, we show what it looks like if you center the expansion around a point that is not at the center of the domain, but rather at the edge."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "b5446b26-2cc9-42ec-b8ad-1ba5ddf23d30",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def func(x):\n",
    "    if isinstance(x, taylor_model):\n",
    "        return sin(x)\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return np.sin(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "exp_points = {\"x\": 0.9}\n",
    "dom = {\"x\": int_d(-1.0, 1.0)}\n",
    "rem = int_d(0.0, 0.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax = plot_orders(func, rem, exp_points, dom, orders=[4, 5, 6], buffer=0.0)\n",
    "ax.grid()\n",
    "# ax.set_ylim([-5, 5])\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('f(x)')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('x');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "63b266b4-c9e0-49b3-9439-ea9ef7714bf5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6-th order power-sine\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, a 6-th order power-sine function is used as a more challenging example. The Taylor model of the function is evaluated on the domain $[-0.5, 1.0]$. The function is defined as:\n",
    "$$f(x) = x \\cdot (x - 1.1) \\cdot (x + 2) \\cdot (x + 2.2) \\cdot (x + 2.5) \\cdot (x + 3) \\cdot \\sin(1.7 \\cdot x + 0.5)$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "8948cbfc-5382-4154-b047-6c3018e463a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def func(x):\n",
    "    if isinstance(x, taylor_model):\n",
    "        return x * (x - 1.1) * (x + 2) * (x + 2.2) * (x + 2.5) * (x + 3) * sin(1.7 * x + 0.5)\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return x * (x - 1.1) * (x + 2) * (x + 2.2) * (x + 2.5) * (x + 3) * np.sin(1.7 * x + 0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "exp_point = {\"x\": 0.0}\n",
    "rem_bound = int_d(0.0, 0.0)\n",
    "domain = {\"x\": int_d(-0.5, 1.0)}\n",
    "\n",
    "ax = plot_orders(func, rem_bound, exp_point, domain, orders=[5, 6, 7], buffer=0.0)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('x')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('f(x)');"
   ]
  }
 ],
